  "scenario": "Phosphoric acid, $\\mathrm{H_3PO_4}$, has **three** acidic protons — it is **triprotic**. But it does not give them up all at once: it ionizes in **stages**, each with its own equilibrium constant, and each $K_a$ is about $10^5$ smaller than the last ($K_{a1} = 7.5\\times10^{-3}$, $K_{a2} = 6.2\\times10^{-8}$, $K_{a3} = 4.2\\times10^{-13}$). So the **first** ionization is the only one that releases an appreciable amount of $\\mathrm{H^+}$ — and it is just the weak-acid ICE table again. Each later stage is the same solve, run on the concentrations the stage before it left behind.",
  "regimes": [
    {
      "facet": "ICE ledger (species accounting)",
      "regime": "ledger-exact"
    },
    {
      "facet": "equilibrium constant",
      "regime": "rule-sourced"
    },
    {
      "facet": "equilibrium position (staged pH)",
      "regime": "model-exact"
    }
  ],
  "assumptions": [
    {
      "claim": "The three ionizations are solved in succession — each stage on the equilibrium concentrations the previous stage left — rather than simultaneously. This is exact in the limit of well-separated $K_a$ (here each is $\\sim10^5$ apart), the standard treatment.",
      "kind": "model"
    },
    {
      "claim": "Water's own autoionization is neglected: $[\\mathrm{H^+}]_0 = 0$ before the acid ionizes (valid because the acid's $[\\mathrm{H^+}]$ is far above $10^{-7}$ M).",
      "kind": "model"
    },
    {
      "claim": "Activities are approximated by molar concentrations — the ideal-dilute-solution model, which is why each $K_a$ is written with concentrations.",
      "kind": "model"
    }
  ],
